"–1262","–1263":"–1263","–1267":"–1267","1085–Male":"1085–Deceased","1090–Female":"1090–Deceased","about 1150":"about 1150","about 1140":"about 1140","1090":"1090","abt 1160":"about 1160","1263":"1263","1262":"1262","1085":"1085","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1118":"1118","1227":"1227","1128":"1128","1267":"1267","um 1118":"about 1118","1207":"1207","Ashburnham, Battle, Sussex, England":"Ashburnham, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Sarre, Kent, England":"Sarre, Kent, England","Ashburnham, Sussex, England":"Ashburnham, Sussex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Criol","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Alberto, Hipolito, Luis, Eriberto, Jose, Luisa, Ramon, Ricardo.  French/Haitian Edwige, Fritz, Serge, Yvrose.","Catalan: from the old personal name <i>Oriol</i>, from Latin <i>Aureolus</i>.","Catalan and French: nickname, possibly for a flamboyant dresser or sweet singer, from Catalan and Old French <i>oriol</i> ‘oriole’ (from Latin <i>aureolus</i> ‘golden’), a species of bird of which the male has bright yellow and black plumage. As a surname of French origin it is also common in Haiti."],"variants":[{"name":"Oriel","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English and Old French female personal name <i>Oriold</i>, <i>Oriel</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Aurildis</i>, <i>Orieldis</i>, composed of elements meaning ‘fire’ + ‘strife’.","French (Vosges): nickname from Old French <i>oriel</i>, a variant of <i>oriol</i> ‘oriole’ (see   Oriol  )."]}]},{"name":"Bertram","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’ + <i>hramn</i> ‘raven’. Ravens were traditional symbols of wisdom in Germanic mythology; Odin was regularly accompanied by ravens called Hugin and Munin. This name was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain.  See also  Bertrand ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Bertram de Criol was born about 1118, in Ashburnham, Sussex, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir John de Criol \"II\", was 35 and his mother, Margery de Criol, was 30. He married Emma Crevequer about 1140, in Sarre, Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1160, at the age of 44."},"et":{"um 1118–abt 1160":"umbes 1118–umbes 1160","1118–1160":"1118–1160","–Female":"Surnud","1128–1207":"1128–1207","1150–1227":"1150–1227","–1262":"–1262","–1263":"–1263","–1267":"–1267","1085–Male":"1085–Surnud","1090–Female":"1090–Surnud","about 1150":"umbes 1150","about 1140":"umbes 1140","1090":"1090","abt 1160":"umbes 1160","1263":"1263","1262":"1262","1085":"1085","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1118":"1118","1227":"1227","1128":"1128","1267":"1267","um 1118":"umbes 1118","1207":"1207","Ashburnham, Battle, Sussex, England":"Ashburnham, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sarre, Kent, England":"Sarre, Kent, England","Ashburnham, Sussex, England":"Ashburnham, Sussex, England"},"fi":{"um 1118–abt 1160":"noin 1118–noin 1160","1118–1160":"1118–1160","–Female":"Kuollut","1128–1207":"1128–1207","1150–1227":"1150–1227","–1262":"–1262","–1263":"–1263","–1267":"–1267","1085–M